{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HG6ScGgACAbJ4bKxqUhatB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's a TypeScript error on line 8 of the test file:\n\n```typescript\nreturn { send: vi.fn<[string], void>() };\n```\n\nThe issue is with `vi.fn<[string], void>()`. In Vitest, the generic signature for `vi.fn` is either `vi.fn<T extends Procedure>()` (single type argument) or `vi.fn(implementation)`. The two-arg syntax `vi.fn<Args, Return>()` is not valid.\n\nLet me fix this:\n- `vi.fn<() => void>()` won't work either\n\n\n- The correct way is to just use `vi.fn()` and let TypeScript infer the type from usage, or cast it as `Mock<(message: string) => void>`\n\nLooking at the Vitest v2.x docs, the signature is `vi.fn<T extends Procedure = Procedure>(fn?: T): MockInstance<T>`, so I could do `vi.fn<(arg: string) => void>()`. But the cleanest approach is to skip the explicit generics and just use `vi.fn()` without type parameters, letting the type system figure it out from context.\n\nDefining the Socket type and mock...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":516,"cache_read_input_tokens":74849,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":516},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"55beee22-13df-4723-9d47-0d074ee65835","uuid":"ca70cbfe-0b34-4a9b-a7af-318b250d0e07","request_id":"req_011CbRTYDDwDaKLtLFSf3Sm7"}
